English: <s>Palu is the capital of Central Sulawesi province, located at the end of a narrow bay on the west coast of Sulawesi island, with an estimated population of 379,800 in 2017.</s>
Spanish: <s>Palu es la capital de la provincia de Sulawesi Central, ubicada en el extremo de un estrecho canal en el oeste de la isla de Sulawesi, con una población estimada de 379,800 en 2017.</s>

History.

The name "Palu" is derived from the Sanskrit word "Palā" (पाला) meaning "salt". The name is also found in the name of the nearby island of Palu, which is also known as "Sulawesi".

The first known mention of Palu was in the "Nagarakretagama", a Javanese chronicle of the Majapahit Empire, which was written in 1365. The chronicle mentions that the king of Sulawesi, Dapunta Hyang, sent a tribute of salt to the Majapahit kingdom.

The Portuguese explorer Francisco de Almeida visited Palu in 1521. He described it as a "very large city" with a population of about 10,000.

History.

The town was first settled in 1732 by a group of Quakers from New Haven, Connecticut. The town was named after Warren, Connecticut, the hometown of the first settlers. The town was incorporated in 1749.

Geography.

Demographics.

As of the census of 2000, there were 1,549 people, 597 households
